title: IKEA Lack box for Prusa i3 MK2 - modified for 0.22in thick plexiglass

description.text:
All credit to the original: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1914314

This is my remix to use thicker glass (0.22 inch acryllic, which is what I found at home depot).

I love this design, but it did take me a bit to fully figure it out. I made a few of my own modifications to it, and there are a few things I'm strongly considering doing that I either didn't have time or didn't have parts to do on this build (and I need to move to other projects for a bit).

Instructions:

There are 3 models for corner pieces; one is a generic (corner1_0.225in.stl) that holds glass on both sides, the other two (corner2_b_0.225in.stl and corner2_a_0.225in.stl) are left and right that hold glass on one side and have a stop on the other. Print four of corner1 and two each of the others. One will go between each table leg and the table itself and one will go under the leg above the base board.

It wasn't clear to me from the original model, but this enclosure does require a bottom to it. I used a 1/2" MDF board and just cut it to the same dimensions as the LACK table -- more or less. I'm impatient, it was raining, and I normally cut things outside... so I cut it with a circular saw without a table, which produced slightly uneven results. So sue me.

Anyway, I purchased a 72"x48" sheet of 0.22" acrylic / plexiglass clone from Home Depot and cut it in a variety of ways. I think the best easy way is probably to get a halfway decent circular saw blade (one with a lot of teeth) and go slow, but I also tried using a cutting tool (from home depot) to score halfway through the acrylic and breaking it and also using a jigsaw with a special blade. The jigsaw was much easier, but with both saws I ended up being too impatient to get a really clean edge.

All of that said, I think it would have been easier to find a place (quick google search turned up http://www.tapplastics.com/product/plastics/cut_to_size_plastic/acrylic_sheets_clear/508) which would let me order them pre-cut; not just easier, but also only very slightly more expensive. You choose =]

Anyway, putting it together is pretty straightforward; I modified the hinges to lay flat. I used http://a.co/3NQzZaW to hold the hinge to the glass (note the version of the hinge with 3 holes on the glass side) and http://a.co/iwv7c2z to hold the hinge to the wood. Make sure you don't drill too large of a hole for those screws; the legs aren't that robust, so you want as much grip as you can get from the screws. Same with the glass; I didn't need nuts on the other side because those screws will dig into the plastic just fine.

I found that with the thicker glass the original smaller magnet size wasn't good enough so I modified the handle and door stop to use 20x2mm (3/4" x 1/16") neodymium magnets.. mostly because I had them. Search ebay for "3/4 x 1/16 Inch Neodymium" and you'll find plenty of options to buy them.

For the lights I used a pair of LED rigid strip lights from eBay and a 45W 12V LED power supply with a inline rocker switch. I had to cut a notch in the edge of the glass on each side to allow the USB and power cables in; I'll likely do something similar when I add a camera.

Future considered mods:

  • Move the power supply to the outside of the glass so it isn't affected by the heat
  • Strap / bolt down the printer to the base so that it can't move and to reduce vibration
  • Move the rambo (control) board outside of the enclosure, which would probably require lengthening most of the wires
  • Move the control head outside of the enclosure

Good luck!

description.text:
'Corner Drawers' are just that... small sets of drawers made to go in a corner. This provides a simple solution to put corner spaces to good use. The design includes upper and lower runners acting on the drawers so, regardless of the triangular shape, the drawers slide straight in / out without skewing sideways.

You can store all sorts of small things in your corner drawers including nuts / bolts / screws, stationary items like paper clips and staples, rubber bands, twist ties, electrical components, jewellery, small toys, parts... and lots more.

Six frame options have been provided so you can print the Corner Drawer set to suit your needs. The differences are the number of drawers and the height of those drawers. The drawer depths differ as follows:

Small (S): 25mm tall
Medium (M): 37.5mm tall
Large (L): 50mm tall

The frame files are named according to the drawers that will fit into them. For example, the SML.stl frame takes one of each of the above drawers. The ML.stl file takes one M and one L drawer... and so on. This provides a range to suit different needs.

The clearances applied should allow the drawers to slide in and out freely. Even smoother sliding can be achieved by spraying some silicone lubricant (or similar) onto the frame rails at the bottom of each drawer slot and in the slots under the drawers themselves. These rails and slots have been designed in so the drawers slide straight in and out regardless of having no side support to stop them from skewing sideways.

Handy for your own use but equally good as a gift. Print in your own choice of colour to make them fit the space. They will look great in any colour combination including subtle / all one colour, classy / neutral colour frame with drawers a different colour or fun / bright with all parts in different colours. Have fun creating your own unique set.

Please refer to the images and print settings for additional information... and post images of your Corner Drawers in use for others to see.

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my practical and fun designs.

iPad Mini stand for rear passengers in a Prius. This is a remix from:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:104534 This one preserves the ability to use at two different angles, and works great when the iPad has a simple rubber case (for me an inexpensive one from Amazon by Tech Armor). I made the overall case wider, rounded the edges on the outside, and beveled the inside edge to match the angle of the iPad. The extra width makes it more stable if touching it while using the stand and fits the width of the armrest in the Prius.

Printed in PLA with 0.3mm layer height on a Bukobot. I set slic3r to do solid infill every 15 layers.  
Used a file to quickly remove any rough spots on the edges that touch the iPad. I have a case on the back and a screen protector on the front so I didn't worry about the iPad beyond this.  
The center armrest locks in a retracted position to access a second cup holder in the front.  Using several Velcro straps interlocked together (these are found at the hardware store) I was able to strap the stand on the armrest extended into the back seat area.  The audio input and power are in the armrest, so there are no wires in the way up front.   Set the audio fader to rear speakers.  The iPad Mini fits well between the front seats.  If you are worried about it falling off, run a piece of Blue Painters Tape up the back of the stand onto the back of the iPad.

description.text:
Tired of rolling erratically while wearing off your hardwood floor? Replace your casters with slippers. The stems have slight fins that progressively squeeze them in as you push (unlike the snap system of the commercial ones) but it holds equally well. They fit a chair bought at Staples, so I'd assume it is the standard caster stem size.

You'll need slipper cushions you can buy at a dollar store, 27mm max diameter. The underpart have a slight dent so the cushions hold better. I warmed the plastic with a butane lighter before sticking them for extra bonding.

Been testing them for more than 6 months now and they hold well (PETG), they slide well, and they look OK.

UPDATE 3/31/2017

Added new Carriage that I redesigned and a new mount that fits it.

===================================================================

UPDATE 1/3/2017

There are many different versions of the SmartrapCore. It has been revised by Smartfriendz many times since they first released it.

This design only works for the original carriage with 8 mm rods. But since it looks like new versions have different carriages, I've uploaded the STEP files for the mount and clamp if you want to edit the design. OR you can download the 8 mm rod carriage from here.

I originally found it at https://www.youmagine.com/designs/smartcore (under download, V1.2, click the gear and then edit in OpenJSCAD) which allows you to adjust parameters and set the rod sizes to 8 mm.

===================================================================

This is my design for an E3D extruder mount that fits the SmartrapCore. It's sturdier, simpler, and can be installed on the 8mm rod x-carriage.

It also provides enough room to use Tom114's E3D integrated layer fan design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1746358 which uses a 50mm radial/blower fan along with the original Prusa i3 mk2 fan nozzle.

With the Smartfriendz extruder mount, I only used the bottom two mounting holes of the carriage with the top two slots of extruder mount. This was necessary to put the nozzle low enough as the E3D v6 isn't very long. But it wasn't a sturdy setup.

This design uses all four holes and incorporates seated nuts.

Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S2wzockz7Bo

comments.text:
I think one of the best solution is really to cut out the parts at the top for the linear rods as shown by jerry ciano in your example. In this case you also get rid of some problems caused by slightly bend rods.
The bearing version might also work, but in this case you also need straight and not bended rods (which is unfortunately the best) otherwise it has the opposite effect and wobbles maybe even more.
This Anti-Z-Wobble adapter is not the best solution for all kinds of problems, but it helps to get things running with reasonable quality results, even with a slightly bended rods. And the advantage to raise the whole carriage very easy and didn't stamp your nozzle into the bed, when something with the endstop or autolevel sensor gets wrong.
So I think all variants will work with their own benefits and downsides. Be happy because you are free to choose your right designed solution.
Otherwise... if your printer is perfectly build and leveled and do not have any crappy parts, than you won't need any these solutions :)

The Pegs and Holes probably need cleaned up if supports were used, I normally use an X-Acto knife for doing this.

My 5 Hour Project

I used 3D Builder (On Windows 10) to Emboss a basic cat shape onto a rectangle then saved it as an STL and loaded it in 123D Design. I then slowly made cubes of different sizes and shapes to cut off the excess using the embossed cat as a template, then I created little spheres and looked up a Braille Key and used it to create "CAT" in braille and I merged it onto the cat. After that I cut the cat into three pieces and added a triangle nob/hole on one side and a circle nob/hole on the other. This is probably a very ineffective way to do this sense it took me about 5 hours, but It got the job done!

This is the cat before I cut off the excess.

Détails in french only : sorry !

Pied pour enceinte bibliothèque.
Le montage sur pointes, c'est très bien, mais sur un meuble, ce n'est pas idéal.
En plus il faut : 1 tampon caoutchouc ou feutre, et 1 joint de plomberie 20/27, trouvables en magasin de bricolage.
Le tampon doit être collé sous la pièce P1. Le joint est monté entre la pièce P1 et P2.
La pièce P2, le joint et le tampon sont sensés filtrer chacun certaines fréquences (en rêve ?).
Plusieurs pièces P2 sont possibles en fonction de la souplesse souhaitée ou du poids des enceintes. Il est possible d'en créer d'autres. Attention à l'ajustage entre P1 et P2 : le diamètre extérieur de P2 sera à ajuster en fonction de l'imprimante. Il ne faut pas que ça coince.
Est ce que ça marche ? Chacun se ferra son opinion.
Chez moi, le meuble en dessous faisait un peu "caisson de basse" avec les petits tampons silicone d'origine, rendant les graves trop présents et prolongés. Avec 3 pieds en config P2V3, ça va beaucoup mieux.

description.text: In this instruction you get to know how to build a cargo hook for your Blade B450 X or 3D helicopter. Of course, interface adaptions for other heli classes and types are easy to achieve. Get an impression of it by watching the YouTube video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WkS0qComzhA

Material required:
3D printed parts, 2ea nails diameter 2mm, servo and associated link/rods etc, tie wraps and double tape, metal ring, long lane, 1 free channel on the receiver/radio Step1: Printing 3D
Print your parts with ABS in medium resolution. The base plate was printed in 0,3mm layers but I recommend making them thinner like the hook parts.
Base Plate volume: 21986.54 cube millimeter
Hook part1 volume: 2557.12 cube millimeter
Hook part2 volume: 3461.60 cube millimeter
The pictures do not show the servo arm and servo rod. Step2: surface treat your parts
Smooth the surface of the parts with an acetone steam bath. Instruction is attached as PDF file. After treatment, drill the holes according to your nail diameter and the servo screws. Step3: assembly and installation
Assemble the hook parts and glue the nail head to the base plate. Install the servo and shape the servo rod accordingly. With double tape, I have attached the landing skid to the base plate and secured it with tie wraps.
Now you have two configuration options: place the base plate so the hook is right under the rotor shaft or turn it around by 180 degrees like shown on the pictures. The base plate is attached to the heli frame with double tape as well and secured with tie wraps. The long lane needs to be at least 1.5meters long. Step4: testing and lift-off
PRE-FLIGHT CHECK: After installation check the proper release function of the hook. Maybe you need to adjust the travel of the servo. Be sure you can easily operate the release switch on your radio in a case of emergency (e.g. heavy oscillation of the load). The switch should be near your stick and not somewhere far away from your fingers. Also check if the modification has a negative impact on existing control cables or rod. PRECAUTION: Be aware an oscillating, heavy load on a short lane can have a severe impact on the stability of your heli. Perform your first flight with an empty tin or light weight object. Depending on your installation configuration: Keep in mind the center of gravity CG of the heli itself and the potential eccentric force from the cargo hook. BEST PRACTICE: Do not hover too long on the spot. Take off and fly forward slowly but constantly. This can avoid oscillation of the load. Like controlling a crane, placing a cargo needs some practice. Enjoy! UPDATE:
I felt I would need a nicer hook on the lower end of the long lane so I designed one. Actually the hook is based on the geometry and design of Firebird - thank you (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14653). So if you like this heli cargo hook, just print the parts from the attached STL files. You don't own a 3D printer? No problem: go to http://www.3dhubs.com/ , register and select a 3D printer in your neighborhood. Pay online and grab it later. Works fantastic. Note: two parts need to be glued together with acetone. The upper part (grey) will be screwed. The two cylindrical parts should be printed in the same orientation to match best! The curved hook part should be printed horizontally.
